In ASP.NET Core, when both the Controller and Action are marked with authorization attributes, the authorization attribute on the Action takes precedence. For example, if the Controller is marked with [Authorize] and the Action is marked with [AllowAnonymous], the request will be allowed even if the [Authorize] attribute on the Controller requires authentication. Similarly, if the Controller is marked with [AllowAnonymous] and the Action is marked with [Authorize], the request will require authentication.

However, when using a custom AuthenticationHandler or AuthorizationFilter, there is no convenient way to get the higher-priority attribute for the current request endpoint to determine whether it requires authentication. Currently, I use the following method, which works but looks clumsy. I wonder if there is a better way to do this. Thank you.


